      "content": "In that case, you can focus on the differences in social organization, technology, and governance between \"primitive\" societies and \"modern\" civilizations. Primitive societies, like those of indigenous peoples, are often characterized by small, kin-based groups, egalitarian social hierarchies, and limited technological advancements. In contrast, modern civilizations, like those of Western societies, are marked by large, complex societies, hierarchical social structures, and significant technological advancements, such as writing, metalworking, and industrialization. You can also discuss how modern civilizations have developed complex systems of law, governance, and social organization, which are often absent or less complex in primitive societies.",
      "source": "target",
